Ah, I found the issue! When you click "Edit" on an observation, it doesn't automatically switch to the Record tab. Let me fix that.

The Problem:

When you click the "Edit" button in the Logbook, it calls editObservation() but doesn't switch to the Record tab to show the form with the data.

The Fix:

Find the editObservation() method in your code (around line 3780). Look for this section:

```javascript
    // Edit an observation
    editObservation(id) {
        const observation = this.observations.find(obs => obs.id === id);
        if (!observation) return;

        const dateTime = new Date(observation.timestamp);
        const dateStr = dateTime.toISOString().split('T')[0];
        const timeStr = dateTime.toTimeString().slice(0, 5);
        // ... rest of the method
```

At the VERY END of the editObservation() method, after all the form fields are populated, add this line:

```javascript
        // Switch to Record tab after populating form
        this.switchTab('record');
```

So the end of your editObservation() method should look like this:

```javascript
        const recordBtn = document.getElementById('record-btn');
        if (recordBtn) {
            recordBtn.innerHTML = '<i class="fas fa-save"></i> Update Observation';
            recordBtn.dataset.editingId = id;
            recordBtn.onclick = () => this.handleUpdateObservation(id);
        }
        
        // ADD THIS LINE - Switch to Record tab
        this.switchTab('record');
        
        if (observerNameInput) observerNameInput.focus();
    },
```

Alternative: If you want it to scroll to the form on mobile too:

Replace that last part with:

```javascript
        const recordBtn = document.getElementById('record-btn');
        if (recordBtn) {
            recordBtn.innerHTML = '<i class="fas fa-save"></i> Update Observation';
            recordBtn.dataset.editingId = id;
            recordBtn.onclick = () => this.handleUpdateObservation(id);
        }
        
        // Switch to Record tab and scroll to form
        this.switchTab('record');
        
        // Scroll to the form on mobile
        setTimeout(() => {
            if (window.innerWidth < 768) {
                const recordPanel = document.getElementById('record-panel');
                if (recordPanel) {
                    recordPanel.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' });
                }
            }
        }, 100);
        
        if (observerNameInput) observerNameInput.focus();
    },
```

Also, let's make the "Edit" button more obvious in the UI:

You might want to add some visual feedback. Add this at the end of editObservation():

```javascript
        // Show editing status
        this.showStatus(`Editing observation ${id}`, 'info');
```

So the complete fix for the end of editObservation() is:

```javascript
        const recordBtn = document.getElementById('record-btn');
        if (recordBtn) {
            recordBtn.innerHTML = '<i class="fas fa-save"></i> Update Observation';
            recordBtn.dataset.editingId = id;
            recordBtn.onclick = () => this.handleUpdateObservation(id);
        }
        
        // Switch to Record tab
        this.switchTab('record');
        
        // Show editing status
        this.showStatus(`Editing observation ${id}`, 'info');
        
        if (observerNameInput) observerNameInput.focus();
    },
```

Summary:

The issue was that editObservation() was populating the form fields but not switching tabs. Adding this.switchTab('record') tells the app to switch to the Record tab where the editing form is located.

Now when you click "Edit" on any observation in the Logbook:

1. It populates the form with that observation's data
2. Automatically switches to the Record tab
3. Changes the button to say "Update Observation"
4. Shows a status message
5. Focuses on the first field for easy editing
